WHILE IN ROUTE TO SAFETYKLEEN, DRIVER HIT A ROUGH SECTION OF ROAD THAT CAUSED THE REAR DOOR OF END-DUMP TO SLIGHTLY OPEN UP AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL CAME OUT.  SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY WHICH WAS LESS THAN TWO MILES AWAY IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED AND PICKED MATERIAL UP AND PUT IT BACK INTO THE END DUMP.  A STREET SWEEPER WAS THEN USED AND PICKED UP THE RESIDUALS.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT HYDRAULIC LOCKING DEVICE ON THE REAR OF TRAILER WAS OUT OF ADJUSTMENT, THIS AND TWO OTHER DAMAGED LOCKING DEVICE CONTRIBUTED TO THE INCIDENT. TRAILER # 3092 WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE AND SENT TO MECHANIC TO MAKE REPAIRS, AND ADJUSTMENTS.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING IN THE FED EX BLDG. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS THE PACKAGE CONTAINED 4 , 1 GALLON CONTAINERS IN A FIBERBOARD BOX OF SEALER P606. ALSO IN THE BOX WERE 6 PLASTIC TUBES OF SOME OTHER MATERIAL. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS WERE REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER. THEY SENT ONE FOR THE P606 NOT THE TUBES. THE FLASH POINT IS 90 DEGREES F. AS THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED OR SENT TO A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS, IT IS BELIEVED TO BE DANGEROUS GOODS. FAA WAS NOTIFIED. FED EX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING INVESTIGATION.

THIS PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS OF THE PLASTIC COOLER,  IT CONTAINED WET ICE WHICH WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE ITEM ACTUALLY LEAKING, AND TWO BROWN BOTTLES IN SHRINK WRAP. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED BY LOCAL FED EX PERSONNEL TO OBTAIN A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET ON THE CONTENTS OF THE BOTTLE. THE MSDS WAS FOR ISOPROPANOL, WITH A FLASH POINT OF 17 DEGREES C. AS THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED, OR SENT WITH SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS, IT IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. FAA AGENT WAS NOTIFIED FED EX IS HOLDING THE SHIPMENT PENDING INVESTIGATION. I CALLED TO NOTIFY THE SHIPPER OF THE PROBLEM WITH THE FREIGHT AS A COURTESY CALL AND WAS THEN TOLD THAT THE ISOPROPANOL WAS NOT IN IT'S PURE FORM AND HAD BEEN MIXED WITH WATER. I REQUESTED AN ACCURATE MSDS BUT WAS TOLD THAT THEY ONLY HAD IT AVAILABLE IN THIS FORM FROM THE MANUFACTURER BUT THEY WERE SURE IT WAS NOT HAZARDOUS IN THE SOLUTION IT WAS IN. I PHONED FAA TO PASS ALONG THIS INFORMATION IN CASE HE WANTED TO HAVE THIS MATERIAL TESTED AT A LAB TO CONFIRM THE CORRECT FLASH POINT. AT THAT TIME FED EX WAS STILL HOLDING THE SHIPMENT AND MR. CLOYD HAD NOT YET SEEN THE FREIGHT AS HE WAS SCHEDULED TO LOOK AT IT ON FRIDAY.

column168: PACKAGE BEGAN LEAKING IN THE PACKAGE HOLDING AREA AT THE STATION AFTER INITIAL DELIVERY ATTEMPT. THE VAPORS CAUSED AN EMPLOYEE AND A CLEANING PERSON TO BECOME NAUSEA AND SLIGHTLY SHORT OF BREATH. THE PACKAGE WAS MOVED TO AN OPEN AREA WHERE THE SPILL CLEAN UP AGENT PERFORMED THEIR SPILL CLEAN UP PROCEDURE PER FED EX POLICY. THE FED EX EMPLOYEE AND A CUSTODIAL EMPLOYEE WERE CHECKED OUT AT THE LOCAL HOSPITAL AS A PRECAUTION AND WERE FINE. UPON INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE WHILE THE SPILL AGENT WAS PERFORMING THE CLEAN UP, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THIS PACKAGE CONTAINED 4 SEPARATE CONTAINERS OF A 2 PART SOLUTION AND 1 PART (500 ML TOTAL) WAS ACETIC ACID SOLUTION. LINDA WILLIAMSON OF THE FAA WAS CONTACTED AND THE DRUMMED PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING A FAA INSPECTION AND DISPOSITION.

THIS PACKAGE HAD 10 INNER CONTAINERS PACKED IN AN INTERMEDIATE PLASTIC BAG AND THEN IN A STRONG OUTER BOX. THE BOX WAS WET WITH WHAT WAS BELIEVED TO BE 30 ML OF SOLUTION. UPON INSPECTION DURING THE SPILL CLEAN UP PROCEDURE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE INTERMEDIATE BAG WAS PUNCTURED AND THERE WAS AT LEAST ONE INNER PACKAGE THAT WAS NOT CLOSED WELL ENOUGH TO PREVENT ANY LEAKAGE. PROPER FED EX SPILL CLEAN UP PROCEDURE WAS PERFORMED AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED. THE SHIPPER INSTRUCTED FED EX TO DELIVER THE PACKAGE, SINCE THE CONTENTS WERE NEEDED FOR A MEDICAL STUDY.

BRAD DIGGS WAS UNLOADING THIS SHIPMENT FROM A STORAGE UNIT . HE THEN LOADED THIS ONE BOX UP IN THE NOSE OF A CITY UNIT. WHEN HE SIT THE BOX DOWN ON TOP OF ANOTHER SKID HE NOTICED THE BOX STARTED LEAKING. UNKNOWING THAT THIS WAS A HAZ MAT SHIPMENT BECAUSE THERE WAS NO HAZ MAT STICKER AND THERE WASEN'T ANY MARK IN THE PM COLUMN ON THE BILL,HE PICKED THE BOX UP AND CARRIED IT TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILOR. HE SAID THAT WHEN HE NOTICED A HAZ MAT LABEL ON THE BOX. HE THEN PULLED THE DOOR DOWN AND NOTIFIED A LEADMAN. I CHECKED THE ER HANDBOOK THEN CALLED DOTHAN. I WAS ABLE TO SPEAK WITH EDDIE YANCE FOR FUTHER INSTRUCTIONS. I SPOKE WITH MR.YANCE AT 04:10 O'CLOCK. HE INFORMED ME TO PUT ON PROTECTIVE GEAR.PULL OFF THE BOX AND PUT IT OUT 0940 BAY . CLEAN THE SPILL WITH QUICK DRY.HE WOULD THEN CALL THE SHIPPER IN THE MORNING. WE FOLLOWED THROUGH WITH THESE INSTRUCTIONS.

AFTER BEING UNLOADED INTO THE WAREHOUSE, THE DRUM IN QUESTION LOST ITS INTEGRITY AND SPLIT DOWN THE SIDE CAUSING A SPILL OF FIVE GALLONS ONTO THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR.   THE DRUM WAS OVER PACKED FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION, AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING CORN COBB.  TWENTY GALLONS OF WASTE WAS GENERATED.  THIS WAS TRANSPORTED TO SAFETY-KLEEN'S PERMITTED TSDF LOCATED AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD DENTON, TX  76208.   THE MATERIAL WILL BE RECYCLED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT SIMILAR INCIDENTS IN THE FUTURE, IT WAS REEMPHASIZED TO THE DRIVER TO CHECK THE CONDITION OF THE DRUMS BEFORE LOADING.

PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATION INDICATES THE HAND BRAKE ON THE CAR WAS RELEASED BY PERSON(S) UNKNOWN, ALLOWING THE CAR TO ROLL OVER A DERAILER DEVICE PREVENTING THE CAR FROM ROLLING ONTO THE MAINLINE. THE INVESTIGATION CONTINUES. THE CAR WAS UP RIGHTED AND RE-RAILED AFTER THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. THE CAR WAS RE CONSIGNED TO A LOCATION APPROXIMATELY 12 MILES AWAY AND MOVED UNDER AUTHORITY OF FRA-9809165, COPY ATTACHED. THE CAR WILL BE UNLOADED AND SHOPPED FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIRS. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED AND/ OR NEUTRALIZED BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.

PAILS WERE STACKED 4 HIGH, SHRINK WRAPPED, AND IN TRANSIT THEY FELL OVER STRIKING EACH OTHER. NO DUNNAGE WAS UTILIZED BETWEEN THE SKIDS TO HELP BLOCK/BRACE PAILS. CLASSIC EXAMPLE OF WHY PAILS STACKED MORE THAN 2 HIGH WILL NOT RIDE IN TRANSIT, EVEN THOUGH SHRINK WRAPPED WHICH DOESN'T CONSTITUTE AS PROPER BLOCKING/BRACING.

THE TWO GLASS 16 OZ BOTTLES CONTAINED WHAT APPEARS TO BE CORROSIVE LIQUIDS. SHIPPER NOTIFIED AND ACKNOWLEDGED THAT SOMEONE MESSED UP AND THAT THE HAZARDOUS SHOULD HAVE BEEN PACKAGED SEPARATELY.  THE ONLY BROKE BOTTLE WAS THAT THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  TWO EMPLOYEES GOT MINOR SKIN BURNS FROM COMING IN CONTACT WITH THIS LIQUID  BUT DID NOT SEEK MEDICAL ATTENTION AT THE TIME.  PACKAGE HELD AT STATION AWAITING FAA INVESTIGATION.

THE DRUM HAD BEEN FILLED AT A HOUSEHOLD HAZARDOUS WASTE COLLECTION EVENT. VARIOUS FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS FROM HOUSEHOLDS WERE CONSOLIDATED INTO THE DRUM. WE BELIEVE SOME SORT OF EXPANDING FOAM WAS THE CAUSE OF THE INTERNAL PRESSURE AS THERE WAS A LARGE QUANTITY OF SOLID MATERIAL LEFT IN THE DRUM THE LIQUID SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP AT THE STORAGE FACILITY IN ACCORDANCE WITH STATE CLEAN-UP REGULATIONS, BY GENERAL CHEMICAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL. THE COMPANY IS REVIEWING VARIOUS PROCEDURAL CHANGES DESIGNED TO REDUCE THE POSSIBILITY OF UNEXPECTED CHEMICAL REACTION WITHIN WASTE CONSOLIDATION CONTAINERS AT OUR HOUSEHOLD WASTE COLLECTIONS.

CAR REPORTED VENTING ON INTERCHANGE TRACK. BNSF HAZMAT RESPONDER INVESTIGATED. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THE REVEALED THE RELIEF VALVE STUCK OPEN AND COULD NOT GET VALVE TO RESEAT. CAR WAS MOVED BACK TO BOC GAS (AIRCO) TO REPLACE THE VALVE.

THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.

column168: WHEN THIS HEAVYWEIGHT CRATE WAS BEING FORKLIFT, IT FELL AND UPON CONTACT WITH THE CONCRETE FLOOR IT RELEASED ABOUT 1-2 GALLONS OF FUEL AND OIL. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED  IN ABSORBANT MATERIAL IN A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO GATHER MORE INFORMATION ABOUT FUEL AMOUNTS IN THE ENGINE. FEDEX WAS TOLD THAT THE ENGINE HAD BEEN TESTED AND ONLY CONTACTED FUEL IN THE FUEL FILTER. SINCE THERE WAS A RELEASE OF FUEL, THE FAA WAS CONTACTED ABOUT THIS POSSIBLE NONDECLARED SHIPMENT. THE CRATE WAS HELD PENDING FAA INSPECTION.

SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AT THE FRONT COUNTER. SERVICE AGENT ASKED THE SHIPPER ABOUT THE "ORM-D" CONSUMER COMMODITY MARKING ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE SHIPMENT. SHIPPER CATEGORICALLY DENIED ANY DANGEROUS GOODS INSIDE THE PACKAGE AND DECLARED THE BOX WAS BEING REUSED (SEE ATTACHED NOTES AND COPY OF AIRWAY BILL). LATER DURING PM OPERATIONS AN ODOR WAS DETECTED WITH THIS SHIPMENT. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED 12 ONE PINT METAL CANS OF "CONKLIN 4-POWER GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL SYSTEM CLEANER". THE FLAMMABLILITY RATING ON THE CANS INDICATED A "4" WHICH IS CONSIDERED THE HIGHEST FLAMMABLE RATING. ONE OF THE PINTS CANS HAD LEAKED ITS CONTENTS  THROUGH THE CAP AND HAD BEEN ABSORBED BY THE PAPER TOWELS INSIDE USED AS CUSHIONING AND THE FIBERBOARD BOX ITSELF. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR FAA INSPECTION AND THE ST.LOUIS FAA OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED ON 9/21/98

FIVE OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE, ETCX 30008, SEPTEMBER 5, 1998, INDIANAPOLIS DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 1320 HOURS, SATURDAY, SEPTEMBER 5, 1998, AT HAWTHORN YARD IN INDIANAPOLIS, INDIANA, A SAVAGETRANSLOADING EMPLOYEE NOTED VENTING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR ETCX 30008 CONTAINING ACETALDEHYDE. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS, CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE VAPOR LEAK  WAS FROM FIVE (5) OF EIGHT (8) MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER WHO TIGHTENED FIVE (5) OF EIGHT (8) MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS. AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

column168: INTERSTATE CONSOLIDATION TRUCKING COMPANY WAS UNLOADING AT AVERITT'S DOCK WHEN A DOCK ASSOCIATE DISCOVERED A BOX ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER THAT WAS WET AND LEAKING. THE DICK ASSOCIATE PUT ON GLOVES AND REMOVED THE ATN FROM THE TRAILER. IT APPEARED THE CTN HAD FALLEN OFF OF A PALLET, DURING TRANSIT, AND ONE OF THE BOTTLES INSIDE THE CTN HAD BROKE. THE ENTIRE CONTENTS IN THE BOTTLE HAD LEAKED OUT. A COMMERCIAL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COMPANY WAS CALLED AND THEY CAME AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND DISPOSED OF THE CTN AND BROKEN BOTTLE.  THE DOCK ASSOCIATE THAT WAS INITIALLY INVOLVED IN THE HANDLING OF THE DAMAGED CTN, WAS SENT TO A MINOR MEDICAL CLINIC FOR PRECAUTIONARY MEASURES. HE WAS GIVEN A CLEAR DIAGNOSIS AND WAS SENT BACK TO WORK.

column168: THE DRIVER PULLED UP TO THE DELIVERY SITE, HOOKED UP TO THE UNLOADING STATION AND OPENED THE CUSTOMER'S PRODUCT DELIVERY VALVE. THEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK, FOLLOWED BY THE WHEEL VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK.  THE DRIVER CLIMBED UP AND OPENED THE AIR INLET VALVE ON TOP OF CARGO TANK AND THEN WENT TO THE TRACTOR AND TURNED ON THE TRACTOR AIR SUPPLY. THE DRIVER THEN RELIEVED THE AIR PRESSURE IN THE CARGO TANK AND MADE TEMPORARY REPAIRS TO THE RUPTURE DISK.  THE DRIVER THEN FINISHED DELIVERING THE LOAD.  THE CUSTOMER CLEANUP AND DECONTAMINATION OF THE AREA OF THE SPILL.

WE PROVIDE ALL INFORMATION HEREIN AS A FACTURAL REPRESENTATIONOF EVENTS KNOWN TO BE THE BEST OF OUR KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITY.

DOCK EMPLOYEE LOADED THE HAZMAT SHIPMENT.  PLACED DUNNAGE PALLETS AGAINST IT.  HE THEN LOADED A SKID OF ANGEL BAR AGAINST THE DUNNAGE. ONE OF THE BARS PENETRATED THE DRUM CAUSING A PUNCTURE CAUSING A LEAK.

DRIVER STARTED TO UNLOAD TRAILER AND WHEN HE OPENED THE VALVE, PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK AT A WELD IN THE FOUR-BOLT FLANGE AT A CONNECTION TO A FILTER.  UNLOAD PROCESS WAS STOPPED, AND DRIPPING CONTINUED UNTIL THE "SOCK" IN THE FILTER DRAINED.  CUSTOMER PERSONNEL DILUTED THE PRODUCT ON THE GROUND AND USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL PADS TO CLEAN IT UP.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.

THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THE SPILL WHEN HE ARRIVED BACK AT THE FACILITY.   HE DID NOT SECURED THE LOAD AND A FIVE-GALLON PLASTIC DRUM FELL OVER RELEASING LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF WASTE INTO THE BED OF THE TRUCK.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH PADS THAT WILL BE CONTAINERIZED AND TRANSPORTED TO SAFETY-KLEEN'S PERMITTED TSDF LOCATED AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE, SE HEBRON OH., 43025.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF WASTE WAS GENERATED.  THE WASTE WILL BE RECYCLED. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN COUNSELLED ON HOW TO PROPERLY LOAD AND SECURE HIS SHIPMENT.

A PINHOLE LEAK DEVELOPED IN A DRUM PREVIOUSLY LOADED ONTO THE TRUCK. AS SOON AS THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL WAS MITIGATED.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH PADS THAT WILL BE CONTAINERIZE AND TRANSPORTED TO SAFETY-KLEEN'S PERMITTED TSDF LOCATED AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE, SE HEBRON OHIO 43025.  aPPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF WASTE WAS GENERATED.  THE WASTE WILL BE RECYCLED. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON INSPECTING THE DRUMS SHE ACCEPTS FOR TRANSPORTATION.

THE DRIVER OVER FILLED THE DRUM BEYOND CAPACITY CAUSING TETRACHLOROETHYLENE TO RUN DOWN THE SIDES AND ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND PLACED INTO A DRUM.  THE DRUM.  WAS STORED AT THE CLEANERS FOR FUTURE PICKUP AND DISPOSAL.

THIS SPILL WAS DISCOVERED BY THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK IN ROUTE TO A PERMITTED TSDF.  SINCE THE WASTE WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRUCK TRAILER, THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO THE TSDF WHERE HE WAS ABLE TO DETERMINE THE SIZE AND EXTENT OF THE SPILL AND HAD RESOURCES TO AID IN THE CLEAN-UP.  ONCE AT THE FACILITY, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT SEVEN GALLONS HAD SPILLED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE DRUMS.  THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED WITH 50 LBS., OF OIL DRI WHICH WAS OVERPACKED ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED DRUM.  THE WASTE WILL BE PROCESSED AT THE FACILITY WHICH IS A PERMITTED TSDF.   THE ADDRESS OF THE TSDF IS 581 MILLIKEN DR., SE, HEBRON, OHIO  43025.  TO AVOID FUTURE INCIDENTS, EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO VISUALLY INSPECT ALL DRUMS PRIOR TO LOADING AND SHIPMENT.

column168: DRIVER PROCEEDED TO RAIL TERMINAL WITH BELIEF THAT CARGO TANK WAS EMPTY AND HAD BEEN CLEANED. HE PRESENTED THE TRAILER FOR LOAD HYDROCHLORIC ACID, UNKNOWING THAT THERE WAS RESIDUE OF BLEACH (SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE) IN THE CARGO TANK. WHEN SHIPPER ADDED 400 GALLONS OF ACID, CHLORINE GAS BEGAN TO BE GENERATED BY THE CHEMICAL REACTION OF TWO INCOMPATIBLE CHEMICALS. VAPORS SPREAD TO NEIGHBORING FACILITY-WHELAND FOUNDRY, AND FOUR EMPLOYEES WENT TO THE DISPENSARY WITH SYMPTOMS OF EXPOSURE. WATER WAS ADDED TO MIXTURE TO ATTEMPT TO DILUTE THE REACTION, AND THE CARGO TANK WAS CLOSED UP AND SENT TO CARRIERS FACILITY. TWO MORE PERSONS BOTH EMPLOYEES OF ARROW TERMINALS,INC. @ THE RAIL YARD WERE SENT FOR CHECK UP AT THE MEDICAL FACILITY. (LIST OF ALL PERSONS TREATED ARE ATTACHED).

MIXING OF INCOMPATIBLE CHEMICALS WAS DONE AT ANOTHER SITE THE ARROW TERMINALS/CSX/B.I.D.S. RAIL YARD AND CARGO TANK WAS SEALED AND BROUGHT TO CARRIER FACILITY. CONSULTATION WAS MADE WITH CORPORATE ADVISORS ON HOW TO NEUTRALIZE THE REACTION IN THE CARGO TANK. EXCESS PRESSURE WAS SCRUBBED THROUGH A NEUTRALIZING SOLUTION. THERE WAS A BRIEF ADDITIONAL RELEASE OF CHLORINE GAS VAPORS , DURING WHICH ONE PERSON WAS AFFECTED AND REMOVED FROM SCENE TO BE TREATED. (LIST ATTACHED) ADDITIONAL WATER WAS ADDED TO DILUTE REACTION , AND TRAILER AGAIN SEALED. STEPS HAVE BEEN TAKEN TO DEDICATE TRAILERS TO THE TWO SEPARATE PRODUCTS TO PRECLUDE A RE-OCCURRENCE.

THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

column168: DRIVER OFF LOADING PRODUCT INTO CUSTOMERS TANK USING AIR PRESSURE FROM HIS TRACTOR.  JUST AS THE TRAILER EMPTIED AND AIR WAS BLOWING THRU HOSE AND CUSTOMER LINE, THE PRODUCT HOSE RUPTURED ABOUT THE HALF WAY DOWN THE LENGTH OF THE 20 FOOT HOSE.  THIS CAUSED A RELEASE OF PRESSURE SPRAYING VAPORS AND RESIDUE INTO THE AIR.  THE UNIT WAS PARKED ON A DRIP PAD OVER A PIT.  THE RESIDUE WAS SPRAYED DOWN WITH WATER BY PLANT PERSONNEL AND THE RUNOFF WENT INTO THEIR PIT.  TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES, I HAVE INSTRUCTED DRIVERS TO CHECK HOSES ON OSMOSE TRAILERS PRIOR TO LEAVING FOR DELIVERY AND IF NEED BE PICKUP HOSES FROM DSI TO BE SURE.  CHECKED WITH OSMOSE MANAGEMENT AND THEY DO HAVE HOSE TESTING PROCEDURES.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, A PALLET WAS FOUND WITH EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE. DUE TO A STRONG ODOR, A CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM WA CALLED TO THE SCENE. ALL CARTONS WERE OFF LOADED FROM TRAILER INTO DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUMS AND INTO RESPONSE TEAM TRUCK. AS THE DRUMS WERE BEING CLOSED, A LIGHT RAIN STARTED TO FALL, AND ONE DRUM SELF IGNITED, BURST INTO FLAMES AND IGNITED THE RESPONSE TRUCK. THE TRUCK AND ALL FIFTEEN CARTONS WERE TOTALLY INCINERATED. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND CHEMTREC WERE BOTH NOTIFIED, AND AN INVESTIGATION IS ONGOING AS TO CAUSE OF THE FIRE.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, A DRUM WAS FOUND THAT HAD TIPPED OVER AND HAD BEEN PUNCTURED. ALL SPILLAGE WAS ABSORBED AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.

column25: BLUE GRASS CHEM SPEC CO INC
column168: ONE DRUM WAS DAMAGED BY BEING PUNCTURED BY OTHER FREIGHT. ALL LEAKAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG AND THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH PROPER LABELS AND MARKINGS. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

UPON ARRIVAL AT RECEIVER,WHILE UNLOADING THE FORKLIFT DRIVER FOUND ONE DRUM LEAKING. THE RECEIVER THE DRUM TO BE LEAKING DUE TO THE BOTTOM CLOSURE NOT BEING PROPERLY SEALED. THE RECEIVER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE, CLEAN THE TRAILER AND DISPOSED OF THE CONTAINMENTATED PRODUCT. APPROXIMENTLY 1/2 GALLON OF THE PRODUCT HAD SPILLED IN THE TRAILER.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE RECEIVER, WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER IT WAS DISCOVERED BY THE RECEIVER TO HAVE LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT IN THE TRAILER. APPROXIMENTLY 2 GALLON OF LIQUID HAD SPILLED. THE RECEIVER TOOK CARE OF THE  C AND DISPOSED OF THE PRODUCT  FOR US. THE EMERGENCY NUMBER OFF THE BILLS WERE C AND  THE INCIDENT WA RECORDED BY BAYER.

column168: DRIVER FAILED TO NEGOTIATE CURVE IN ROADWAY AND CROSSED FROM NORTHBOUND LANE ACROSS SOUTHBOUND LANE, AND WENT THROUGH GUARD RAIL, CUT  DOWN A UTILITY POLE AND ROLLED OVER ON AN EMBANKMENT. THE UTILITY POLE PUNCTURED THE CARGO COMPARTMENT. MOST OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT  SOLIDIFIED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND 50 GALLONS REACHED THE GROUND AND SOLIDIFIED. DRIVER WAS KILLED BY THE COLLISION, NOT  THE PRODUCT. PRODUCT WAS 430 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT AND A DECISION WAS MADE TO ALLOW THE MATERIAL TO SOLIDIFY INSIDE THE WRECKED TRAILER OVER THE WEEKEND PRIOR TO ATTEMPTING TO REMOVE THE WRECKED TANK. TRAILER AND ITS CONTENTS ARE TO BE CUT INTO 3 FOOT SECTIONS FOR DISPOSAL. WORK TO BE DONE BY MCCUTCHEON ENTERPRISES OF APOLLO, PA. ON DAY OF ACCIDENT, ROAD WAS CLOSED AND A TOWN WAS WITHOUT ELECTRICAL POWER FOR 9 HOURS. ON  DAY OF REMOVAL, ROAD WAS CLOSED 5 HOURS.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: DRIVER WES REBERT ARRIVED AT BETHLEHEM STEEL SPARROWS POINT, MD PLANT. AT 1130 HE STARTED UNLOADING THE 93% SULFURIC ACID. AT APPROXIMATELY 1154, 26 MINUTES INTO THE OFFLOADING PROCESS, THE PRODUCT UNLOADING HOSE RUPTURED CAUSING 150-200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND AT THE UNLOADING STATION. BETHLEHEM STEEL AND BALTIMORE COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED AS WELL AS BEN SMITH FROM ENVIRITE OF PENNSYLVANIA AND THE MDE INSPECTOR RAYMOND WINGO. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT  THE PRODUCT UNLOADING HOSE WAS DEFECTIVE. MOBILE DREDGING CO. WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. PREVENTATIVE MEASURES FOR THE FUTURE INVOLVE DAILY INSPECTIONS OF THE PRODUCT UNLOADING HOSE.
THE CHICAGO FETTING AN THE TRAILER WAS LOOSE 7 LEAKED. CUSTOMER CLEANED UP BY WASHING PRODUCT INTO CUSTOMER SYSTEM.
DRIVER PUT CAPS ON HOSES AND THE GASKET WERE BAD & HOSES LEAKED.
TRAILER LEAKING AT THE SEAM. DRIVER CATCHING IN BUCKETS. USED ABSORBANTS TO WIPE UP.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT DOW PLANT AND WAS SENT TO CONNECT TO TRAILER 7966. DRIVER FAILED TO CONNECT THE BRAKING SYSTEM LINES AND TRAILER ROLLED BACKWARDS AS DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO GET TRACTOR UNDER IT. IT BUMPED INTO THE LINES ATTACHED TO A TRAILER DIRECTLY BEHIND IT (6086) AND THE LINES WERE SNAPPED OFF. DOW CHEMICAL CO. PERSONNEL STOPPED THE LEAKAGE  AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL. NO OTHER DAMAGES WERE DONE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES. THERE WAS NO ESCAPE OF MATERIALS TO ANY WATERWAYS.

column168: WHILE THE YARD CREW WAS PERFORMING SWITCHING OPERATIONS THEY SMELLED A STRONG ODOR OF PROPANE.  YOUNG ENV., WAS REQUESTED TO RESPOND. THEY FOUND THAT RAIL TANK CAR MTCX 504 HAD A LOOSE PACKING NUT AROUND THE GAUGING DEVICE. THE LOOSE PACKING NUT WAS TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.  ALL THE REQUIRED NOTIFICATION WERE MADE.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: DODX 14334, RES AVIATION FUEL, REPORTED BY SWITCH CREW TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT ON NORFOLK SOUTHERN INTERCHANGE.  CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, DEPT OF DEFENSE, THEY ARE NOT ABLE TO ASSIST WITH A RESPONSE.  CSXT RESPONDED FOUR SEASONS ENVIRONMENTAL, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, OUT OF GREENSBORO, NC.  THE OP CTR REPORTED CAR INSPECTORS CHECKED CAR AND FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET BELL CAP WAS CROSS THREADED, THEY BACKED THE CAP OFF AND RETIGHTEN IT. THIS STOPPED THE LEAK.  FOUR SEASONS ON SCENE REPORTED NO LEAKAGE.  SMALL STAIN ON BALLAST AND SOME ODOR.  CHECKED AREA WITH OVA; NO PROBLEMS.

TILX 250129, LD OF PETROLEUM DISTILLATE, WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A SPLASH LEAK FROM HE TOP WHEN IT WAS MOVED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN RUSSELL, KY.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER REQUESTED THE CONSIGNEE TO RESPOND.  THE CAR WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE GASKET ON THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE.  THE CONSIGNEE CONTACTED RESCAR, A RAIL CAR REPAIR CO., TO REPAIR THE CAR.  RESCAR FOUND THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE GASKET WAS OK.  THEY FOUND THE EDUCTION PIPE ITSELF WAS NOT PROPERLY SEATED IN THECAR CAUSING THE PHLANGE ON THE PIPE TO BE "COCK".  THIS  PREVENTED THE GASKET FROM FORMING A GOOD SEAL BETWEEN THE PHLANGE AND THE VALVE.  RESCAR RESET THE PIPE AND INSTALLED THE VALVE AND GASKET.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

column168: Personnel working in the area around to utlx 130245, observed a "white mist", escaping from the top of the car. Inspection showed that the manway lid was loose and humidity in the area was reacting with the acid vapors left in the car. The car was isolated and the consignee for the car was notified. The consignee sent a contractor to repair/ secure the car. The loose fitting was secured and the release of vapor ceased. All other fittings were inspected and found to be secure.

The car foreman at csxt's rail yard in Detroit, MI, reported utlx 48354, ld of turpentine was leaking from the top when moved. The consignee and owner of the product was notified. They sent an emergency response contractor, Youngs Environmental, to repair the leak. The contractor reported that the release occurred at the vacuum relief valve on the manway cover. The "O" ring on the vacuum relief valve was pinched and the product sloshed from around the valve when the car was moved. The contractor replaced the "O" ring, secured the vacuum relief valve and the car was released.

column168: While loading a 6700 water gallon cargo transport trailer with ammonium hydroxide (aqua ammonia solution) a meter bypass valve partially opened. The partial opening of this valve allowed product to flow into the trailer without being metered. The meter is designed to shut off the pump at a preset amount. Because of the bypass flow, the meter did not reach the preset amount and the trailer overfilled. The material spilled onto the parking lot where it was diluted by facility and Philadelphia Fire Dept. personnel and allowed to evaporate into the atmosphere. The puddle was contained to the parking lot area and did not threaten any sewer/ storm drains or any natural bodies of water.

column168: A 55 GALLON DRUM WITH AN APPARENT UNSEALED SPOUT CONTAINING WASTE WATER SULFURIC ACID WAS OVERPACKED BY THE CUSTOMER INTO AN 85 GALLON DRUM WITH A SCREW TOP LID.  (NOTE: WE DO NOT HAVE ANY INFORMATION TO INDICATE IF THE INITIAL 55 GALLON DRUM FAILED, THIS IS WHY THE BOXES IN COLUMN "A" ARE NOT MARKED FOR BLOCKS 41,42,43,44, AND 45.) WHEN THE 85 GALLON OVERPACK WAS SUBSEQUENTLY PICKED UP BY A SAFETY-KLEEN OTR DRIVER, THE OVERPACKED DRUM WAS TILTED DOWN AS IT WAS BEING LOADED ONTO A TRUCK AND FELL OFF THE PALLET.  AS IT WAS LYING ON THE GROUND, THE SCREW TOP LID OF THE OVERPACK APPARENTLY WAS NOT FULLY SECURE DUE TO THE PRESENCE OF THE PROTRUDING SPOUT AND A SMALL QUANTITY OF THE WATER SULFURIC ACID WAS SPILLED.  IT APPEARS THAT THE MATERIAL MAY HAVE LEAKED OUT OF THE UNSEALED SPOUT. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED WITH APPROXIMATELY 25 POUNDS OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PUT INTO THE OVERPACK ALONG WITH THE 55 GALLON DRUM.  THE WASTE WAS SHIPPED FOR PROCESSING TO A PERMITTED SAFETY-KLEEN TSDF LOCATED AT 633 E 138TH STREET, DOLTON, IL 60419 FOR PROPER TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. PROVIDED INVOLVED PERSONNEL WITH TRAINING ON PROPER CLOSURE SPECIFICATIONS FOR THE SPECIFIC TYPE OF 85 GALLON PLASTIC OVERPACK INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT.

TUB SKIDS WERE SITTING ON PAD WAITING TRANS-SHIPMENT.  THE TOP SKID LEAKED ONTO THE LID OF THE ONE BELOW.  THE TOP SKID WAS DOUBLE WRAPPED IN VISQUEEN AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL RETURNED TO THE PACKAGE.  NO WASTE REACHED THE GROUND.

column168: OUR TRUCK/CARGO TANK WAS TRAVELING WEST ON US HWY 62 AND FAILED TO NEGOTIATE A CURVE KNOWN LOCALLY AS "DEAD MANS CURVE" AND TURNED OVER.  THE CARGO (DIESEL FUEL) WAS IMMEDIATELY PUMPED OUT OF THE CARGO TANK USING FUEL TRUCKS.  ALL BUT 868 GALLONS WAS RECOVERED FROM THE CARGO TANK.  AFTER THE FUEL WAS REMOVED THE TRUCK/CARGO TANK WAS TAKEN TO KENNETT, MO BY LOWRY'S WRECKER SERVICE.  ARKANSAS DEPARTMENT OF POLLUTION CONTROL AND ECOLOGY WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY.  REMOVAL OF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS BEGUN THE NEXT MORNING PER INSTRUCTIONS FROM ADPC&E.  THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL, KEPT FOR OBSERVATION OVERNIGHT AND RELEASED THE NEXT MORNING 9-29-98.

GATX 97643, September 14, 1998, Philadelphia Division. At approximately 1455 hours, Monday, September 14, 1998, while exiting Tanner Industries in Havre De Grace, MD, a Conrail conductor and engineer reported product escaping from the loading/ unloading hose that had been previously connected to tank car GATX 97643 containing ammonia, anhydrous, liquified. Appropriate notification made. Approximately three pounds of product was released from the hose. An employee from Tanner Industries closed the partially open valve and cleaned the spilled area. For precautionary measures, Conductor W.R. Thompson, employee number 085857 and Engineer M.E. Foster, employee number 758282 were taken to John Hopkins Bayview Hospital, Baltimore, MD. Examination revealed on ill effects of product and normal blood oxygen level. No lost time days.

Mission driver was at the customers location. When he was unloading, the vent on the dome lid was not working properly. This caused a ten gallon spill of crude oil. AFC Lease Service contained and cleaned up the spill. The contaminated product was properly disposed of. The driver was verbally warned and counseled on this incident.

Mission driver was at the customer's location. When he was unloading, he overfilled the product tank causing a 20 gallon spill of diesel. Garner Environmental was called to the scent to contain and clean up the spill. The contaminated soil was stored for proper disposal. The driver received a verbal warning on this incident.

Driver checked trailer when he took a break at a truck stop and found product dripping slowly from the trailer external valve (qrv valve). He summoned help. Driver backed trailer into an unload position and the trailer was tiled down grade with the rear end considerably lower than the front end. When the driver opened the air valve to apply pressure to the trailer, the "head" pressure of the liquid was sufficient to force liquid into the air line and product entered the compressor prior to the compressor having built up sufficient pressure to overcome the "head" pressure of the liquid cargo. Product leaked from the compressor housing into a plant containment area. Customer personnel cleaned up and neutralized the spilled material. There were no injuries and no product reached any waterways.

column168: EIGHT OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE, NATX 38428, SEPTEMBER 13, 1998, PHILADELPHIA DIVISION.   AT APPROXIMATELY 1900 HOURS, SUNDAY, SEPTEMBER 13, 1998, AT CPS CHEMICALS IN OLD BRIDGE, NEW JERSEY, A CONRAIL TRAIN CREW NOTED COMMODITY LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR NATX 38428 CONTAINING  FUSEL OIL.  INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO CPS CHEMICALS PLANT MANAGER WHO ADVISED HE WOULD HANDLE. AS REPORTED BY PLANT MANAGER THAT DURING INTERNAL INVESTIGATION OF INCIDENT, TANK CAR'S MANWAY COVER HAD BEEN OPENED TO OBTAIN SAMPLE OF PRODUCT AND WAS NOT RE SECURED AFTERWARD.  REPORTED ALL MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE APPLIED, BUT NOT SECURED TOOL TIGHT.  REPAIRS WERE MADE BY CPS CHEMICALS WHO TIGHTENED EIGHT (8) OF EIGHT (8) MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS AT TIME OF INCIDENT.  CPS ADVISED SPILLED PRODUCT CONTAINED IN AREA AS DESIGNED AND HANDLED FOR REMEDIATION BY CPS PLANT PERSONNEL.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: WHILE PULLING CARS FROM POLLUTION CONTROL INDUSTRIES, THE GATX96840 WAS COUPLED INTO TO SET BACK TO THE INDUSTRY TRACK.  WHEN COUPLED INTO MATERIAL SPILLED OUT OF DOME COVER BECAUSE IT WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED.  GATX 96840 WAS NOT YET READY FOR SHIPMENT.  A CAR BEHIND GATX 96840 WAS ORDERED TO BE SHIPPED.  INDUSTRY WAS ADVISED TO PROPERLY SECURE HATCH COVERS OF CARS WHICH HAD TO BE MOVED ASIDE. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY POLLUTION CONTROL INDUSTRIAL AND WILL BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  ATTACHED IS A COPY OF A EXAMPLE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST WHICH WILL BE USED WHEN THE MATERIAL  IS ACTUALLY SHIPPED.   POLLUTION CONTROL INDUSTRIES (PCI) HAS AGREED THAT A TRAINED PCI EMPLOYEE WILL PERFORM AN INSPECTION OF EACH RAIL CAR PRIOR TO REMOVAL OF THE BLUE FLAG.  THE INSPECTION WILL BE DOCUMENTED AND MAINTAINED ON-SITE.  ADDITIONALLY, EACH GASKET ON THE DOME LID WILL BE REPLACED AND THEN WRENCHED TIGHT PRIOR TO MOVEMENT.

DUANE HELTON, PVS DRIVER, HAD LOADED HYDROCHLORIC ACID AT ATOCHEM LOADING RACK AND DRIVEN TO ATOCHEM SCALE ACROSS PENNSYLVANIA/BIDDLE. ATOCHEM NIGHT SUPERVISOR NOTICED SPILL/DRIPS ON STREET AND CALLED FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND BLEW SIREN.  DUANE WAS UNAWARE OF LEAK AND WAS ALREADY ON SCALE, DID NOT REALIZE THAT HE HAD CAUSED THE ALARM AND WAS TRYING TO EXIT THE AREA THE AREA QUICKLY TO GET OUT OF THE WAY OF WHAT HE THOUGHT WAS A PLANT PROBLEM.  FIRE DEPARTMENTS FROM RIVER VIEW AND WYANDOTTE RESPONDED AND CLEANED UP SPILL WITH SODA ASH/WATER.  DUANE PULLED OFF SCALE.  AL ISENEGGER RESPONDED TO DUANE'S CALL TO PVS DISPATCH AND IDENTIFIED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AS THE RUPTURE DISK ON THE TRAILER.  AL WORKED WITH DUANE TO CHANGE THE RUPTURE DISK.  SPILL WAS NOT REPORTABLE, ESTIMATED BETWEEN ONE AND THIRTY GALLONS.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE FACILITY SOME PRODUCT WAS NOTICED AROUND THE DRUM ON THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN.  THE FACILITY UNLOADED THE DRUM AND CLEANED THE TRAILER.  THE DRUM HAD A VERY SMALL PUNCTURE AND SEEPAGE WAS COMING FROM IT.

MISSION DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE THE BLEEDER VALVE ON SUMP PRIOR TO UNLOADING.  THIS CAUSED A 10 TO 15 GALLON SPILL OF FUEL OIL.  THE CUSTOMER CALLED AN OUTSIDE AGENT TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN-UP THE SPILL. THE DRIVER RECEIVED A WRITTEN WARNING AND WAS COUNSELED ON THIS INCIDENT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: MISSION DRIVER HOOKED UP TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT AND WHEN HE TURNED THE PUMP THE FITTINGS BROKE CAUSING A 15 GALLON SPILL OF GASOLINE. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED-UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED.  THIS WAS AN EQUIPMENT FAILURE.  THE DRIVER WAS NOT AT FAULT.

MISSION DRIVER WAS LOADING CRUDE OIL.  HE FAILED TO TAPE THE EARS ON THE HOPE.  THIS CAUSED A SPILL OF 100 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL.  AN OUTSIDE AGENT CLEANED-UP THE SPILL AND IT WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED. THE DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW COMPANY POLICY AND HE RECEIVED FIVE DAYS OF SUSPENSION.

THE CUSTOMER BLEEDER VALUE WAS LEAKING.  THERE WAS A THREE GALLON SPILL OF DIESEL.  THE SPILL OCCURRED AFTER THE DRIVER LEFT CARROLL PETROLEUM.  THE DRIVER DIDN'T USE THE CUSTOMER'S VALVE.  CARROLL PETROLEUM CONTAINED AND CLEANED-UP THE SPILL.  THE DRIVER IS NOT AT FAULT.

MISSION DRIVER HAD TO CONNECT TWO HOSES TO REACH THE UNLOADING HEAD. HE SPILLED APPROX., 1 TO 2 GALLONS OF DIESEL TRYING TO DRAIN THE HOSES.  THE DRIVER CONTAINED AND CLEANED-UP THE SPILL.  THE CUSTOMER LOCATION DOES NOT HAVE THE PROPER ACCESS TO THE UNLOADING POINT.  WE ARE NO LONGER SERVICING THIS LOCATION DUE TO THIS MATTER.

SHIPMENT OF BAGS LOADED ON TOP CF LEAD DECK AND ONE BAG WAS TURN CAUSING PRODUCT TO SPILL OUT.  PRODUCT LOST WAS MINIMAL.  PROBLEM MAY HAVE BEEN CAUSED WHILE LOADING TRAILER AND PUSHING A SKID INTO THE BAGS CAUSING TEAR AND 1 CAR LACK OF DUNNAGE.

column168: DRIVER PICKED UP THE CONTAINER AT THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION AND WAS ISSUED A NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST. THE MATERIAL INSIDE THE CONTAINER SHIFTED TO THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER "PUSHING" THE TAILGATE AWAY FROM THE SEAL CAUSING THE MATERIAL TO RELEASE ONTO THE GROUND BEHID THE CONTAINER.  ALL OF THE MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED UP AND PLACED BACK INTO THE CONTAINER FOR DISPOSAL.  THE MATERIAL WAS ANALYZED AND FOUND TO BE HAZARDOUS FOR P.H.

column62: Over-pressurized; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER GOING AROUND CURVE ON RURAL MOUNTAIN ROAD.  TIRES DROPPED ONTO SOFT SHOULDER AREA AND TRUCK SLID INTO DITCH.  TRUCK ROLLED ON SIDE.  SOME HIGH PRESSURE CYLINDERS WERE THROWN ON GROUND BUT NONE FAILED.  DUE TO NORMAL WARMING OF REFRIGERATED LIQUID THE OXYGEN AND NITROGEN BEGAN TO VENT THROUGH SAFETY RELIEF VALVES.  THIS WAS NORMAL VENTING OF NON-FLAMMABLE GASES ON DOT 4L CYLINDERS.  AFTER THE TRUCK WAS RIGHTED, THE CYLINDER PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED AND VENTING STOPPED.  DRIVER SUFFERED ONLY MINOR CUTS AND BRUISES.  NO OTHER VEHICLES OR PERSONS INVOLVED.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: (A-J) WHEN THE DRIVER CARRYING THE SHIPMENT (WHICH INCLUDED THE 55 GALLON DRUM CONTAINED THE OVERPACKED CONTAINER OF NITRIC ACID PREVIOUSLY HANDLED BY NATIONAL VACUUM) FROM LACKAWANNA, NEW YORK ARRIVED AT THE EAST AVON, NEW YORK ACCUMULATION CENTER AT APPROX 8:15PM, ANOTHER WORKER NOTICED SMOKE COMING OUT OF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THE FACILITY CONTINGENCY PLAN WAS IMPLEMENTED BY CALLING THE FIRE DEPARMENT, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AND DESIGNATED INTERNAL PERSONNEL.  WHEN 2 INDIVIDUALS FROM THE LCOAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM, ARRIVED SHORLY THEREAFTER, THEY ATTEMPTED TO LIFT THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRUCK.  WHILE TYE WERE UNABLE TO OPEN THE DOOR ALL THE WAY, THEY ALLEGEDLY OBSERVED A GLOWING RED 55 GALLON DRUM WITH CORN COB ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK.  A FORKLIFT WAS USED TO LIFT THE DOOR. THEREAFTER, THE ROOF OF THE TRAILER WAS EJECTED ALLOWING OXYGEN AND RAINFALL TO ENTER THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER.  THIS CHAIN OF EVENTS APPARENTLY LED TO THE EXPLOSION OF THIS PARTICULAR DRUM, WHICH THEREAFTER SET THE REMAINDER OF THE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER ON FIRE.  THE FIRE EVENTUALLY SPREAD TO THE EXTERIOR OF THE ACCUMULATION CENTER BUILDING AS WELL AS AN ADJACENT TRACTOR/TRAILER.  BOTH TRUCKS IMPACTED BY THE FIRE CONTAINED HAZARDOUS WASTES IN STORAGE INCIDENTAL TO TRANSPORTION.  BASED ON PRELIMINARY INFORMATION RECEIVED FROM THE LIVINGSTON COUNTY OFFICE OF EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT SERVICES AND THE NEW YORK STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION, THIS DRUM IS SUSPECTED TO BE THE PRIMARY CAUSE OF THE FIRE.

column168: (A-J) WHEN THE DRIVER CARRYING THE SHIPMENT (WHICH INCLUDED THE 55 GALLON DRUM CONTAINED THE OVERPACKED CONTAINER OF NITRIC ACID PREVIOUSLY HANDLED BY NATIONAL VACUUM) FROM LACKAWANNA, NEW YORK ARRIVED AT THE EAST AVON, NEW YORK ACCUMULATION CENTER AT APPROX 8:15PM, ANOTHER WORKER NOTICED SMOKE COMING OUT OF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THE FACILITY CONTINGENCY PLAN WAS IMPLEMENTED BY CALLING THE FIRE DEPARMENT, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AND DESIGNATED INTERNAL PERSONNEL.  WHEN 2 INDIVIDUALS FROM THE LCOAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM, ARRIVED SHORLY THEREAFTER, THEY ATTEMPTED TO LIFT THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRUCK.  WHILE TYE WERE UNABLE TO OPEN THE DOOR ALL THE WAY, THEY ALLEGEDLY OBSERVED A GLOWING RED 55 GALLON DRUM WITH CORN COB ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK.  A FORKLIFT WAS USED TO LIFT THE DOOR. THEREAFTER, THE ROOF OF THE TRAILER WAS EJECTED ALLOWING OXYGEN AND RAINFALL TO ENTER THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER.  THIS CHAIN OF EVENTS APPARENTLY LED TO THE EXPLOSION OF THIS PARTICULAR DRUM, WHICH THEREAFTER SET THE REMAINDER OF THE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER ON FIRE.  THE FIRE EVENTUALLY SPREAD TO THE EXTERIOR OF THE ACCUMULATION CENTER BUILDING AS WELL AS AN ADJACENT TRACTOR/TRAILER.  BOTH TRUCKS IMPACTED BY THE FIRE CONTAINED HAZARDOUS WASTES IN STORAGE INCIDENTAL TO TRANSPORTION.  BASED ON PRELIMINARY INFORMATION RECEIVED FROM THE LIVINGSTON COUNTY OFFICE OF EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT SERVICES AND THE NEW YORK STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION, THIS DRUM IS SUSPECTED TO BE THE PRIMARY CAUSE OF THE FIRE.

column168: THE WAREHOUSE MANAGER MOVED A PALLET CONTAINING THE NITRIC ACID CONTAINERS FROM THE TRANSFER STORAGE AREA IN THE WAREHOUSE ONTO THE LOADING DOCK.  THE PALLET WAS LOADED ONTO THE TRUCK.  AS THE CONTAINERS WERE BEING LOADED ONTO THE TRUCK FROM THE  PALLET, THE WAREHOUSE MANAGER NOTICED THAT THE FINAL CONTAINER WAS LEAKING ONTO THE PALLET AND THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK.  THE WAREHOSUE MANAGER ALERTED THE ON-SITE EMERGENCY COORDINATOR TO THE SPILL AND PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENT PADS.  THE COORDINATOR IMPLEMENTED THE EMERGENCY CONTINGENCY PLAN AND CALLED A THIRD PARTY CONTRACTOR-- NATIONAL VACUUM, INC.-- TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL AND COMPLETE THE ASSOCIATED CLEANUP ACTIVITIES.  NATIONAL VACUUM PLACED THE LEAKING FIVE GALLON CONTAINER INTO A 16 GALLON OVERPACK AND USED CORN COB AS THE ABSORBENT/PACKING MATERIAL.  THE SPILL RESULTED IN THE GENERATION OF APPROXIMATELY 16 GALLONS OF WASTE IN THE INITIAL OVERPACKED DRUM AND A SECOND 16 GALLON DRUM OF CLEANUP DEBRIS INCLUDING THE ABSORBENT PADS, BROKEN UP PALLET AND ADDITIONAL CORN COB MATERIAL.  THE INITIAL 16 GALLON OVERPACK WAS PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON OVERPACK WITH VERMICULITE USED AS PACKING  MATERIAL AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE BY THE SAFETY-KLEEN STAFF PRIOR TO BEING SHIPPED THE EAST AVON ACCUMULATION CENTER.  THIS DRUM IS SUSPECTED TO BE THE PRIMARY CAUSE OF A SUBSEQUENT FIRE WHICH OCCURRED SEVERAL HOURS LATER AT THE EAST AVON, NEW YORK ACCUMULATION CENTER FACILITY. THE SECOND DRUM WAS NEUTRALIZED THE NEXT DAY WITH LIME AND SENT TO THE SAFETY KLEEN PROCESSING FACILITY AT 6125 NORTH PECATONICA RD, PECATONICA, IL 61063 FOR PROPER TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  EMPLOYEES WILL RECEIVE TRAINING ON THE PROPER HANDLING OF NITRIC ACID PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION OF THIS MATERIAL.

DEFECTIVE TANK CAR LINER, GATX13945, SEPTEMBER 28, 1998, TOWANDA DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1710 HOURS, MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 28, 1998, AT THE LEHIGH SECONDARY TRACK ADJACENT TO THE OSRAM SYLVANIA PLANT IN TOWANDA, PA., AN OSRAM SYLVANIA FOREMAN DISCOVERED A STEADY STREAM OF PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR GATX 13945 CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.   AT APPROXIMATELY 2350 HOURS, A CONRAIL MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVED AT THE SITE.  THE CONSIGNEE, OSRAM SYLVANIA PUT A CONTAINMENT POOL UNDER THE LEAK AND RECLAIMED ALL PRODUCT FOR PRODUCTION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0130 HOURS, TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 29, 1998, TRANSFERRING FROM THE TANK CAR DIRECTLY INTO OSRAM SYLVANIA'S STORAGE TANK COMMENCED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0215 HOURS, HMHTTC, AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT THE SITE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0430 HOURS, LIQUID PRODUCT ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND TRANSFERRED PRODUCT FROM THE TANK CAR TO THE TRUCK.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0900 HOURS, TRANSFERRING CEASED.  THE PRODUCT FROM THE TRUCK WAS THEN PUMPED INTO THE STORAGE TANK.  HMHTTRC CLEANED AND PURGED THE TANK CAR AND CLEANED THE SPILLED AREA.  THE TANK CAR WAS HOME SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED ALL PRODUCT.   ESTIMATED LOSS OF WAS PRODUCT WAS 300 GALLONS. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD A DEFECTIVE TANK CAR LINER AND THAT PRODUCT PENETRATED THROUGH THE STEEL AT THE BOTTOM OF THE SUMP.

VACUUM RELIEF VALVE STUCK IN AN OPEN POSITION, UTLX 640076, SEPTEMBER 21, 1998, INDIANAPOLIS DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1200 HOURS, MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 21, 1998, AT CONRAIL'S BUCKEYE YARD IN COLUMBUS, OHIO, CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER DISCOVERED PRODUCT VENTING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR UTLX 640076 CONTAINING FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S. (DICYCLOPENTADIENE).  CONRAIL S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER, EXAMINED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS STUCK IN AN OPEN POSITION. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER WHO ADJUSTED THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1230 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED, OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

column62: Derailment; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON 9-25-1998, AT APPROX 1645 HRS, A KCS RAILWAY MANIFEST FREIGHT TRAIN, TRAIN NUMBER #42, WHILE PROCEEDING NORTH BOUND, DERAILED AT KCS MILE POST 713 (APPROX SIX MILES NORTH OF DEQUINCY, LA). THE DERAILMENT WAS CAUSED BY DEFECTIVE LOAD SECURING DEVICES(LOAD SECUREMENT IS THE RESPONSIBILITY OF THE SHIPPER, AND NOT THE RR), INTENDED TO SECURE A LOAD OF SLAB STEAL, WHICH FELL FROM A FLAT CAR WITHIN THE TRAIN, WEDGING ITSELF UNDER THE TRAIN AND CAUSING TWENTY RAIL CARS TO DERAIL AT THE SPEED OF 53 MILES AN HOUR. AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT,  TANK CARS NATX 72446 AND ACFX 82573, LOADED WITH ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES LIQUID, N.O.S., RECEIVED HEAVY DAMAGE TO THE TANK SHELLS RESULTING IN LADING RELEASE. THE LOCAL BEAUREGARD PARISH VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPT IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND DEPLOYED DOWNSTREAM CONFINEMENT MEASURES TO MITIGATE THE RELEASE. KCS EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTORS WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO THE SITE, AND PROVIDED FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONFINEMENT, CONTAINMENT, RECOVERY AND ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION OF THE INCIDENT SITE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESULTED FROM THE RELEASED HAZMAT LADING. THE DERAILMENT OCCURRED WITHIN CLOSE PROXIMITY (APPROX. 100 FEET ) TO LOUISIANA STATE HIGHWAY 27. THE HWY WAS CLOSED FOR A PERIOD OF 60 HRS BY THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE DEPT. TO SAFELY FACILITATE THE TRANSFER OF A  LOADED PROPYLENE OXIDE TANK CAR WHICH WAS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT, BUT DIDN'T RELEASE. AS A PRECAUTIONARY SAFETY MEASURE TO THE LOADED PROPYLENE OXIDE TANK CAR, THE LASPD AND THE BEAUREGARD SHERIFF DEPT ELECTED TO EVACUATE AN ELDERLY MAN WHO LIVED APPROX. ONE HALF MILE FROM THE INCIDENT SITE. ALL EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES WERE CONDUCTED UNDER THE OVER SITE OF THE LASPD, LA DEPT. OF ENVIR QUALITY, AND THE USEPA. ALL WASTE GENERATED FROM THE INCIDENT WAS CHARACTERIZED AND PROFILED FOR PROPER DISPOSITION.

APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. CONRAIL,S DISTRICT MANAGER EXAMINED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT TWO OF FOUR LIQUID LINE VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE BOLTS WERE LOOSE. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY CONRAIL,S DISTRICT MANAGER WHO TIGHTENED TWO OF THE FOUR LIQUID LINE VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE BOLTS. column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: OPEN LIQUID AND VAPOR LINE ANGLE VALVES AND UNSECURED LIQUID AND VAPOR VALVE CLOSURE PLUGS, MBLX 34342, SEPTEMBER 25,1998, PHILADELPHIA DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 0035 HOURS, FRIDAY, SEPTEMBER 25,1998, IN PENCOYD, PA, LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND REPRESENTATIVES FROM PECO UTILITY WERE SUMMONED TO THE AREA OF GLEN ROAD AND THE SCHUYLKILL EXPRESSWAY TO INVESTIGATE THE ODOR OF GAS. INVESTIGATION FOUND TANK CAR MBLX-34342 CONTAINING LIQUID PETROLEUM GAS EMANATING A STRONG GAS SMELL. LOCAL AUTHORITIES CLOSED DOWN THE SCHUYLKILL EXPRESSWAY. FOUR HOMES ON RIGHTERS FERRY  ROAD WERE EVACUATED BY THE LOWER MERION FIRE AND POLICE. THE TANK CAR WAS SITUATED IN TRAIN CAPI-5 THAT HAD STOPPED AT CONRAIL'S WEST FALLS YARD TO ADD CARS. TANK CAR WAS LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILE NORTH OF CITY LINE AVENUE ON AN OVERPASS OVER GLEN ROAD IN LOWER MERION TOWNSHIP. THE RAIL LINE AT THIS LOCATION IS DOWN AN EMBANKMENT JUST TO THE NORTH OF THE SCHUYLKILL EXPRESSWAY. AT APPROXIMATELY 0200 HOURS, CONRAIL'S DIRECTOR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SYSTEM ARRIVED AT THE SITE, AND INSPECTED THE CAR WITH TWO MEMBERS OF THE MONTGOMERY COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM WHO HAD PERFORMED AN INITIAL INSPECTION OF THE CAR. UPON INSPECTING THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AREA, VISIBLE ICING WAS EVIDENT AT THE NOZZLE AND PLUG OF THE A END LIQUID LINE. THE HAZMAT TEAM MEMBERS ALSO INDICATED THAT AN AUDIBLE SOUND AND VAPOR WERE ALSO PRESENT FROM THE NOZZLE  AND CAP OF THE RIGHT SIDE VAPOR LINE. THEY FURTHER INDICATED THAT THEY HAD TIGHTENED  THE PLUG OF THE VAPOR LINE THAT SEEMED TO STOP THE PRODUCT RELEASE. INSPECTION OF THE LIQUID AND VAPOR LINE FOUND THAT BOTH ANGLE VALVES WERE OPEN APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TURN. ADDITIONALLY, BOTH PLUGS WERE SIGNIFICANTLY LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE LIQUID AND VAPOR LINES WERE CLOSED AND THE PLUGS TIGHTENED. AT APPROXIMATELY 0310 HOURS, PRODUCT RELEASE HAD BEEN TERMINATED (ALL OTHER VALVES, FITTINGS AND STUD BOLTS WERE EXAMINED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.)AT APPROXIMATELY 0310 HOURS, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM REACT RESPONDED TO THE SITE. USING APPROPRIATE TOOLS, ALL PLUGS, CLOSURES AND STUD BOLTS WERE AGAIN CHECKED AND PROPERLY SECURED. AT APPROXIMATELY 0330 HOURS, LOCAL OFFICIALS OPENED THE SCHUYLKILL EXPRESSWAY AND TERMINATED THEIR RESPONSE. THE TANK CAR WAS OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

THIS SHIPMENT LEAKED WHILE IN THE WAREHOUSE.  PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A FEDEX SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS THERE WERE SIX PLASTIC BOTTLES IN THE BOX.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET ORIGINALLY FAX'D LISTED THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME AS "OXIDIZING LIQUID, TOXIC, N.O.S., CLASS 5.1 UN3099, SUBRISK 6.1.  SINCE THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED, OR SENT WITH A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IT WAS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  AT THAT TIME I NOTIFIED F.A.A. AGENT LYNN LEONARD. WE WERE HOLDING IT PENDING INVESTIGATION.  IN THE MEANTIME THE CUSTOMER EVIDENTLY TOLD THE FAA THAT THEY SENT THE WRONG MSDS AND THE CORRECT MSDS SHOWS THE PACKAGE CONTENTS AS BEING NON-HAZARDOUS. WHEN THE FAA CONFIRMED THIS TO OUR LOCAL FEDEX FACILITY THEY SENT THE PACKAGE ON THROUGH THE SYSTEM.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 29, 1998, A TRUCK LOADED WITH 14 CONTAINERS OF PADUCAH GASEOUS DIFFUSION PLANT (PGDP) DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY (DOE) LOW LEVEL WASTE (LLW) ARRIVED AT THE HANFORD DOE SITE FOR DISPOSAL.  AS OPERATORS WERE UNLOADING THE CONTAINERS, LIQUID WAS SEEN ON THE TRAILER BED NEAR CONTAINER NUMBER 55419-01, A B-25 BOX CONTAINING PLASTIC DEBRIS, AND SIGNS OF CORROSION WERE NOTED NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX.  RADIOLOGICAL SURVEYS INDICATED CONTAMINATION OUTSIDE THE CONTAINER AT <220 DISINTEGRATION PER MINUTE PER CENTIMETER SQUARED (DPM/CM2) FROM A BETA/GAMMA SURVEY.  DETECTABLE LEVELS OF RADIOLOGICAL CONTAMINATION WERE FOUND ON THE TRAILER BED AND ON AN ADJACENT CONTAINER.  THE OTHER CONTAINERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRUCK LEAVING THE BREACHED CONTAINER IN PLACE.  THE AREA WAS THEN SECURED BY HANFORD WASTE OPERATIONS.  ON OCTOBER 2,  THE TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATED AND RELEASED TO THE OWNER. A TOTAL OF 40 CONTAINERS OF PGDP DOE LLW GENERATED DURING THE C-746 Q DRUM RUPTURE INCIDENT WERE APPROVED FOR DISPOSAL OF HANFORD.  THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF FOUR FLAT BED TRUCKS THAT LEFT PGDP BEGINNING ON SEPTEMBER 24, 1998 WITH THE LAST TRUCK LEAVING ON SEPTEMBER 28, 1998.  ALL TRUCKS HAD ARRIVED AT HANFORD BY OCTOBER 1, 1998.  THE CONTAINER CONSIST OF STABILIZED ACIDIC WASTE AND SECONDARY DEBRIS.  RADIOLOGICAL SURVEYS AND INSPECTIONS OF THE TRUCK AND CONTAINERS SHOWED NO BREACHES OR CONTAMINATION UPON RELEASE FROM PGDP.  THE CONTAINER THAT IS BREACHED IS A B-25 LSA STRONG TIGHT CONTAINER.  THE CONTENTS OF THE BREACHED CONTAINER CONSIST OF USED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, PLASTIC DEBRIS, AND CUT UP PLASTIC DRUM LINERS.  THE CONTAINER HAS A LAYER OF PLASTIC SHEETING COVERING THE INSIDE SURFACE.  IN ADDITION, ALL WASTE WAS PLACED IN RADIOLOGICAL BAGS PRIOR TO CONTAINERIZING. NO FREE LIQUIDS WERE PRESENT WHEN THE WASTE WAS CONTAINERIZED. RADIOLOGICAL DATA TAKEN BY HANFORD SOLD WASTE PERSONNEL FROM THE TRUCK TRAILER AND BREACHED CONTAINER INDICATE THAT THE CONTAMINATION LEVELS ARE UNDER LIMITS ALLOWED BY 49 CFR TRANSPORTATION REGULATIONS.  PADUCAH PROJECT'S BECHTEL JACOBS COMPANY RADIOLOGICAL PROTECTION MANAGER VERIFIED DATA.  CONTRIBUTION WAS LIMITED TO SMALL AREA ON THE BOTTOM OF THE BREACHED CONTAINER,  THE TOP OF THE TRAILER BED, AND ANOTHER BOX.  THE OTHER BOX WAS APPARENTLY CROSSED CONTAMINATED FROM THE FORK LIFT TIMES USED TO MOVE THE CONTAINERS. DISPOSAL ACTIVITIES ARE PENDING FURTHER REVIEW.

column168: RTMX2618, SEPTEMBER 26, 1998, INDIANAPOLIS DIVISION CAR REPORTED LEAKING TO STO BY E.I. DUPONT PERSONNEL LOOKING FOR HELP TO MOVE CAR INTO BELLE PLANT. CAR ON LEASED TRACK AND HAD BEEN REPORTED TO DUPONT BY LOCAL POLICE. CONRAIL CONTACTED BY DUPONT LOOKING FOR AN ENGINE TO MOVE CAR INTO THEIR PLANT FOR FURTHER HANDLING. CAR LEAKING AT BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AT RATE OF 70 DROPS PER MIN. BUCKET PLACED UNDER OUTLET CAP TO CONTAIN MATERIAL. CAR WAS MOVED BY DUPONT RAIL SERVICES (AFTER OBTAINING KEYS FOR DERAIL FROM CONRAIL). DUPONT PERSONNEL HANDLED BY RESPONDING THEIR T.E.R.P RESPONSE TEAM. CAR WAS A RESIDUE CAR RETURNING FOR LOADING. NOTE: OTHER THAN CONRAIL BEING CONTACTED FOR THE USE OF AN ENGINE TO MOVE THIS CAR NO CONRAIL PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN REPORTED LEAKING TO DUPONT UNTIL DUPONT CALLED ASKING FOR THE USE OF AN ENGINE TO MOVE THE CAR INTO THE PLANT.

ASHLAND DRIVER HAD HOOKED THE HOSE TO THE CUSTOMER PRODUCT LINE. THE LINE HAD A VALVE ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BUILDING AND ONE ON THE INSIDE. THE INSIDE VALVE WAS IN AN AREA THAT WAS THE CUSTOMERS RESPONSIBILITY. WHEN THE DIVER STARTED TO PUMP THE PRODUCT THE HOSE RUPTURED FROM PRESSURE CREATED BY THE CLOSED VALVE. THE DRIVER CLOSED THE VALVE ON THE OUTSIDE. CONTAINED MOST OF THE SPILL IN A DIKED AREA. APPROX. 5 GALLONS WAS FLOATING IN A PUDDLE OF RAIN WATER. THE DRIVER PUMPED THE PRODUCT AND WATER FROM THE PUDDLE AND RETURN TO THE PLANT TO BE DISPOSED OF. PADS WERE USED TO CLEAN ANY RESIDUE FROM THE AREA. THE CUSTOMER TOOK RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE DIKED AREA.

DURING ROUTINE FLIGHT FROM MEMPHIS, TN TO BORINQUEN (BQN) PUERTO RICO.  THE CREW OF FLIGHT #57 NOTICED A STRONG ODOR IN THE AIRCRAFT. CREW DETERMINED ODORS WERE COMING FROM THE DANGEROUS GOODS FREIGHT CONTAINER IN POSITION #1 (B-727 AIRCRAFT).  THE FLIGHT CREW DONNED OXYGEN MASKS AND RECEIVED PERMISSION TO LAND IN ORLANDO, FL.  FLIGHT MADE AN UNEVENTFUL LANDING AND PROCEEDED TO THE FEDEX RAMP WHERE OUR DANGEROUS GOODS/SPILL CLEAN UP SPECIALISTS MET THE AIRCRAFT.  DG SPECIALIST CONFIRMED A SHIPMENT OF SEVEN STEEL DRUMS CONTAINING FLAMMABLE LIQUID WERE GIVING OFF THE ODORS.  THE CAPTAIN HAD THE ORLANDO RAMP CREW OFFLOAD THE DANGEROUS GOOD FREIGHT CONTAINER FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND "AIRED-OUT" THE AIRCRAFT.  THE FLIGHT THEN CONTINUED ON TO PUERTO RICO.  FLIGHT #57, A/C TAIL #N220FE.  I MADE TELEPHONE CONTACT TO DOT/COAST GUARD AS REQUIRED BY 171.15 TO "800" NUMBER PETTY OFFICER TURMAN SAID OUR REPORT NUMBER WAS #455752. ALSO CONTACTED HOWARD AUSTEN.  FAA DUTY OFFICER IN ATLANTA FOR SOUTHERN REGION.  FAA DID RESPOND WITH A VISIT TO FEDEX ORLANDO TO INVESTIGATE DRUMS.  DRUMS ARE NOW CONTAINED IN SALVAGE DRUMS AND ARE AWAITING DISPOSITION INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

ON SEPTEMBER 14,1998, FACILITY PERSONNEL WERE PREPARING TO OFF LOAD WASTE DERIVED FUEL FROM A RAIL CAR (GATX 18251) WHEN DURING THE AGITATON PERIOD APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF FUEL BUBBLED OUT OF THE TOP OF THE RAIL CAR. ALL OF THE FUEL DRAINED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE RAIL CAR INTO CONCRETE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AT THE FUELS FACILITY. THE SPILL OCCURED AT 15:10, FOAM WAS APPLIED IMMEDIATELY TO REDUCE VAPORS,ALL FREE LIQUID WAS CLEANED-UP AT 15:45. VERBAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES. THE ENTIRE RELEASE COVERED AN APPROXIMATE 220 SQUARE FOOT AREA. EMISSION CALCULATIONS FROM THE RELEASED VAPORS ARE ATTACHED. THE WASTE CODES ASSOCIATED WITH THE MATERIAL ARE ALSO ATTACHED.THE AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY SECURED USING ABSORBENT PADS AND CLEANING SOLVENT. ALL MATERIALS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WERE PLACED INTO DRUMS AND WILL BE SENT OFF-SITE FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. NO INJURIES WERE ENVIRONMENT REMAIN AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. NO EVACUATION WAS REQUIRED. NO CONTAMINATION OF ANY WATER BODY OCCURED. PLEASE CONTACT ME AT (601)272-6016 OR KEITH BROWN, RESOURCE RECOVERY SUPERINTENDENT, AT (601)272-6026 SHOULD YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS CONCERNING THIS INCIDENT OR THIS REPORT.

column168: ON 9/30/98 LEAD HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORTER, KATHY WICAL REPORTED A SHIPMENT EMITTING AN ODOR AT THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT FACILITY OF ABX AIR, INC. PART TIME HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIANS, RANDY WILLIAMS AND TAMMY FLORENCE RESPONDED UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THE SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED. TECHNICIAN FLORENCE DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE, INSIDE THIS FIBERBOARD BOX WAS A METAL RECEPTACLE WITH A CAPACITY OF ONE GALLON. THIS WAS A FRICTION TYPE RECEPTACLE THAT HAD POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE. THIS CLOSURE WAS NOT PROPERLY PLACED ON THE RECEPTACLE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

OPEN TRAILER DOOR AND COULD SMELL AN ODOR. EMPLOYEE, ZACERY DAVIS, INFORMED THE UNDER SIGN (JOE LEGRAND), THAT SHIPMENT WAS DAMAGED. I INFORMED HIM TO PUT CONTAINER ON CONWAY'S BACK DOCK WHICH IS OPEN AND AWAY FROM PERSONNEL. THERE WAS NO HAZ/MAT PHONE NUMBER LISTED ON THE COSO/BILL OF LADING. LARRY RIFLES, FOS, CALLED INFORMATION WHO SUPPLIED SHIPPER TELEPHONE NUMBER AND CONTACTED CHIP MCLENDON, SAFETY DIRECTOR FOR CONWAY, THE SAME DAY. THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN AN EMPTY TRAILER THAT WAS SEALED AND LOCKED AND WAS MOVED TO AN AREA IN THE YARD THAT WAS SAFE AND WOULD NOT BE DISTURBED AND WAITED FOR FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS. ADDITIONAL NOTE: AS THE BEST OF MY KNOWLEDGE, WHEN I FIRST SAW THE SPILLAGE, I THOUGHT IS WAS LIQUID. UPON FURTHER EXAMINATION I FOUND IT TO BE OF GRANUAL MATERIAL. IT APPEARED TO BE A HANDFUL THAT WAS SWEPT UP AND PUT WITH THE CONTAINER. UPON DISCUSSION WITH THE DRIVER FROM FORT SMITH, ARKANSAS, HE ADVISED ME THAT THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN DAMAGED AT THEIR FACILITY WHEN THEY LOADED IT ON THE TRAILER THAT WAS BROUGHT TO THE Shreveport TERMINAL.

column168: ON 9/25/98, THIS TANK CAR WAS FOUND BY LOCAL RAILROAD FORCES AT LIVONIA YARD TO BE LEAKING ITS CONTENTS FROM A BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AT THE UNION PACIFIC YARD AND MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED. WHILE IN ROUTE TO THE YARD, ROBINSON WAS CONTACTED BY UPRR MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAIN TENANCE, DAVE MYERS. MYERS ADVISED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM A TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, AND THAT HE COULD SAFELY ATTEMPT TO CLOSE THE VALVE FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. MYERS WAS ABLE TO APPLY EIGHT REVOLUTIONS TO THE OPERATING STEM OF THE VALVE AND THIS SECURED THE CAR FROM LEAKING. THE PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED FROM THE CAR EVAPORATED FROM THE BALLAST. UPON ARRIVAL,ROBINSON INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT IT WAS NO LONGER LEAKING. THE CAR WAS SET OUT TO THE HAZ/MAT TRACK AT LIVONIA TO AWAIT INSPECTION BY THE SHIPPER. ADDITIONALLY, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE VIA THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER TO CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER (ASHLAND CHEMICAL), THE LOUISINA STATE POLICE, THE LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.

column168: AT 2300 HRS., SHELL BRIDGEPORT DRIVER JIM POLOWITZ, WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT IN NEWTOWN, CT., AT THE INTERSECTION OF RT. 25 AND MILE HILL ROAD.  WHILE JIM WAS DRIVING ENROUTE TO THE DANBURY STATION ON RT. 25. THE INTERSECTION OF RT. 25 AND MILEHILL RD. HAD AN EMERGENCY DETOUR SET UP BY NEWTOWN  FIRE DEPT.  DUE TO AN EARLY AUTO ACCIDENT OF A LARGE UTILITY POLE WHICH HAD FALLEN INTO THE INTERSECTION AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 P.M. UTILITY WIRES WERE LAYING ACROSS THE INTERSECTION WHICH MADE THE ROAD IMPASSABLE. JIM HAD TO FOLLOW A DESIGNATED ROUTE WHICH HAD BEEN SET UP BY LOCAL OFFICIALS WHICH HAD LEFT THE SCENE PRIOR TO JIM'S APPROACH DUE TO ANOTHER EMERGENCY CALL IN TOWN.  THE ONLY PERSONNEL AT THE TIME WERE UTILITY PERSONNEL IN THE AREA REINFORCING DOWN WIRES.  THERE WERE NO EMERGENCY PERSONNEL DIRECTING TRAFFIC, BUT CONES WERE SET UP IN A NARROW CURVED AREA DUE TO EMERGENCY RESPONSE ALREADY TAKING PLACE AT THE TIME OF JIM'S ACCIDENT.  JIM FOLLOWED THE OUTLINE FOR DETOUR VEHICLES AND WAS FORCED TO JUMP THE CURBING/GRASS AREA WITH HIS RIGHT TANDEMS SINCE HE COULD NOT TURN THE TRACTOR/TRAILER IN A WIDE PATTERN.  WHICH IS TYPICAL FOR THIS TYPE OF TURN.  JIM'S TANDEMS DROVE BY FOUR 2.5 TO 3 FOOT HIGH GUIDE POLES SET BACK APPROXIMATELY 4 FOOT WITH NO PROBLEM APPROXIMATELY 8-10 FOOT FROM THE FIRST SERIES OF GUIDE POLES.  A SECOND SET OF GUIDE POLES NEAR THE CURB LINE BEGAN THE FIRST POLE WAS CAMAFLOUGED WITH HIGH GRASS AND BRUSH.  THIS IS THE POLE WHICH SEVERED THE THREE MANIFOLD VALVES.  JIM FOLLOWED THE SUGGESTED ROUTE BY EMERGENCY PERSONNEL BUT COULD NOT MAKE THE TURN SINCE THE ROUTE WAS EXTREMELY NARROW.  THIS RESULTED IN A SPILL OF 18-20 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WHICH CAME FROM #2,#3 AND #4, MANIFOLDS SEVERED BY THE HARDWARE ON THE HIDDEN GUIDE POLE IN THE SHRUB. AFTER THE PRODUCT ESCAPED FROM THE MAINFOLDS IT IGNITED FROM A SPARK.  THE DRIVER SAW THE FLASH AND TOOK THE UNIT ABOUT 25 FOOT AWAY FROM THE FIRE FOR A SAFE HAVEN AND ABANDONED THE TRUCK SINCE HE WAS NOT SURE IF A TRAIL OF FIRE WAS FOLLOWING DOWN MILE HILL ROAD.   THE FIRE ALMOST EXTINGUISHED ITSELF BUT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN SUMMONED BY THE UTILITY PERSONNEL IN THE AREA.  THEY HAD BEEN IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA FOR A BANK ALARM.  THEY EXTINGUISHED SMOLDERING GUIDE POLE AND SHRUB/GRASSY AREA.  I WAS NOTIFIED BY THE DRIVER AT 2340 HOURS AND WENT IMMEDIATELY TO THE SCENE TO WORK WITH POLICE/NEWTON FIRE DEPARTMENT CT.DOT/ AND CT DEP., WHICH WERE SUMMONED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED PLANT MANAGER AND LYNNE CAME TO THE SCENE FOR SUPPORT AND ACCIDENT/INVESTIGATION ANALYSIS.  I CALLED A.E.T.(ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR) TO RESPOND TO CLEAN AND TRANSFER THE BALANCE OF CARGO APPROXIMATELY 8780 GALLONS FROM THE SHELL TANKER TO TWO VACUUM TRUCKS PER THE REQUEST OF CT. DEP.

FREIGHT WAS CRUSHED BETWEEN 2 SKIDS DUE TO POOR LOADING.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL  DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN IN CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FOR THE EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

ON 9-17-1998 AT 12:00 NOON AMATO DRIVER (MR. JOE BRISCOE), WAS COMPLETING A PERC DELIVERY  AT WOODMOOR CLEANERS IN SILVER SPRING, M.D. WHILE PLACING THE HOSE INTO THE TRUCK MR. BRISCOE TUGGED ON THE HOSE NOZZLE THE HOSE NOZZLE SEPARATED FROM THE END OF THE HOSE RESULTING IN RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT. THE DRIVER WAS AT THE FLOW CONTROLS OF THE TRUCK WHEN THE NOZZLE SEPARATED , AND SHUT THE EMERGENCY FLOW VALVES OFF IMMEDIATELY, STOPPING THE FLOW OF THE PRODUCT.THE PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO AN ASPHALT PARKING LOT IN THE REAR OF THE CLEANING ESTABLISHMENT. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN A SMALL AREA OF THE REAR PARKING LOT USING SMALL ABSORB PADS. THE SPILL, AT NO TIME ENTERED ANY DRAINS OR SEWERS. THE PHYSICAL SIZE OF THE SPILL WAS APPROX. 10 FEET SQUARE IN SIZE. IN ADDITION TO THE DRIVERS EFFORTS,THE AMATO SPILL CLEANUP TEAM WAS DISPATCHED. THE TEAM WAS ON THE SCENE WITHIN 10 MINUTES OF THE INCIDENT. THE SPILL CLEANUP TEAM BEGAN IMMEDIATE SPILL REMEDIATION. THE PRODUCT WAS REMEDIATED WITHIN 20 MIN. AND REMOVED FROM SIGHT. THE ASPHALT IN THE PARKING LOT WAS UNAFFECTED BY THE PRODUCT. THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED WAS 6 GALLONS OF "PERC", A DRY CLEANING FLUID. THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME OF THE PRODUCT AS DEFINED IN 49 C.F.R. PART 172.101 IS AS FOLLOWS RQ-TETRACHLOROETHYLENE,6.1,UN1897,PGIII. THE AMOUNT WAS DETERMINED BY SUBTRACTING 19.1 GALLONS FROM 13.1 GALLONS THAT WAS ON THE METER PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT RESULTING IN THE SIX GALLON DIFFERENCE. THE PRODUCT WEIGHS 13.67 POUNDS PER GALLON FOR A TOTAL WEIGHT OF 82 POUNDS OF PRODUCT. SPILL SORBENT UTILIZED: 1-50 # BAG SPILL SORB SORBENT MATERIAL,1-8' SORBENT BOOM. AFTER SORBENT WERE UTILIZED THEY WERE PLACED IN A HAZ MAT CLEAN UP DRUM AND TRANSPORTED TO STORAGE AT AMATO IND, INC. AWAITING TRANSPORT TO CLEAN AMERICA FOR PROPER RECLAMATION/DISPOSAL.

column168: MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY RICHARD TUFTS WAS CONTACTED BY PAGER BY REGIONAL MGR MIKE SEABAUGH AT 0950 HRS ON 09-19-1998 ADVISING THAT RISK MANAGEMENT DISPATCHER WAS ATTEMPTING TO CONTACT HIM IN REFERENCE TO A TANK CAR AT THE A&S RAILROAD YARD THAT WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING ANHYDTOUS AMMONIA. MGR. TUFTS CONTACTED THE RMCC DISPATCHER AND WAS ADVISED TO CONTACT A&S ASST. SUPERINTENDENT CLARENCE MILLER. FOLLOWING CONTACT WITH MR. MILLER, MGR. TUFTS RESPONDED TO THE A&S WITH A 2 HR ETA FROM JEFFERSON CITY,MO. MGR TUFTS ARRIVED ON SCENE AND PROCEEDED TO APPROACH THE CAR WHICH WAS LOCATED IN THE BOWL. MGR TUFTS DONNED PROTECTIVE CLOTHING AND SCBA AND OPENED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING NOTING THAT THERE WAS A HISSING SOUND AND VAPOR BEING RELEASED FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. MGR TUFTS DETERMINED THAT HE WOULD BE UNABLE TO REPAIR THE LEAK AND CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, C.F. IND., TARLIE BROOKS, AND ADVISED THAT THE CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSLOADED. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON THE IC TRANSFER TRACK AWAY FROM ANY POTENTIAL PUBLIC/ ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT. CHURCH ROAD FIRE DEPT. WAS CONTACTED AND AGREED TO STAND BY WITH WATER SUPPLY TO ASSIST IF NEEDED. MS. BROOKS AUTHORIZED AND CONTACTED KIESEL COMPANY, ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR TO ASSIST IN THE MITIGATION AND TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT. MGR TUFTS CONTACTED THE A&S AND WAS ABLE TO LOCATE A TANK CAR RLC AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS IN THE YARD THAT COULD BE USED AS THE RECEIVING CAR, GATX 58722. KIESEL CO. ARRIVED ON SCENE AT APPRX 1730 HRS. AND PREPARATIONS WERE MADE TO BEGAN THE TRANSFER PROCESS. TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT BEGAN AT 2224 HRS AND FOLLOWING SAFETY AND LEAKAGE TESTS ACTUAL FLOW OF PRODUCT COMMENCED AT 0100 HRS ON 09-20-1998. TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED AT 0600 HRS. AND THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO STAY ISOLATED AND BLEED OFF REMAINING PRESSURE. MGR TUFTS RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. TOM POWELL, II. EPA DURING THE EARLY AFTERNOON AND WAS ADVISED THAT HE HAD BEEN ON THE SCENE TO CHECK ON THE PROCESS OF THE CAR AND NOTED THAT THERE WAS STILL A SLIGHT LEAK FROM THE SAFETY VALVE ALLOWING VAPOR TO VENT. MGR TUFTS RETURNED TO THE SCENE AND NOTED THE LEAK SEEMED MINIMAL AND NOTED THAT THERE WAS VERY LITTLE ODOR IN THE AREA.  MGR TUFTS  AGAIN ATTEMPTED TO ACCESS THE SCENE ON THE EARLY MORNING OF 09-21-1998 AND WAS UNABLE TO GET TO THE SCENE DUE TO BEING BLOCKED BY TRAINS. AT APPROX. 0800 HRS. MR. MILLER CONTACTED MGR TUFTS AND ADVISED THAT THE CAR WAS STILL EMITTING VAPOR. MGR TUFTS CONTACTED KIESEL COMPANY, MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO SCRUB THE VAPORS INTO A TANK TRUCK AND RETURNED TO THE SCENE CONTACTING THE SHIPPER TO ADVISE STATUS, NOTING TANK PRESSURE TO BE 80PSI. VAPORS WERE SCRUBBED THROUGHOUT THE DAY AND AT APPROX. DUSK, THE PRESSURE HAD DROPPED TO 13LBS. AND THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR TURNED TO ICE AS EVIDENCE BY ICE FORMING ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE TANK. THE PRESSURE IMMEDIATELY ROSE TO 20LBS. AND IT WAS FELT THAT SUBLUXATION WAS OCCURRING. SCRUBBING CONTINUED AT A VERY SLOW RATE  AND IT WAS DECIDED TO APPLY HEAT TO THE EXTERIOR OF THE CAR

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RICHARD TUFTS WAS NOTIFIED AT 11:30 ON 09-17-1998 , BY TRACK INSPECTOR RON DEVIAR THAT SEVERAL WORKERS AT THE WANN YARD IN WOO RIVER, IL WERE ATTEMPTING TO PERFORM TRACK WORK AND SMELLED AN ODOR THAT THEY THOUGHT MIGHT BE COMING FROM A TANK CAR. NO SPECIFIC CAR WAS IDENTIFIED HOWEVER MR. DEVIAR ADVISED THAT THERE WAS NUMEROUS LPG CARS IN THE YARD. MGR TUFTS NOTIFIED THE RMCC DISPATCHER AND PROCEEDED EN ROUTE, ARRIVING ON SCENE AT 12:15HRS. MGR TUFTS PROCEEDED TO INSPECT THE CARS IN THE YARD AND LOCATED CAR #UTLX 83000 WHICH WAS A RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS CAR OBSERVING THAT THERE WAS A SLIGHT HISSING SOUND COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING . UPON CLOSER INSPECTION MGR TUFTS FOUND THAT THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE OPEN SYSTEM GAUGING DEVICE WAS NOT SECURE. MGR TUFTS SECURED THE NUT AND STILL NOTED A SLIGHT ODOR IN THE HOUSING REPRESENTATIVE OF A MINOR LEAK. MGR TUFTS CHECKED ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS AND DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A SMALL LEAK OF VAPOR ONLY BEING EMITTED FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. MGR TUFTS CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, CLARK OIL AT HARTFORD , IL. AND ADVISED OF THE FINDINGS AND REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER RESPOND TO ASSIST IN REPAIR OF THE VALVE. UPON THE SHIPPERS ARRIVAL IT WAS DETERMINED THAT CAR WOULD BE PLACED BACK IN THE INDUSTRY TRACK AND THAT THE SHIPPER WOULD REMOVE THE VAPOR IN THE CAR, REMOVE THE VALVE AND MAKE NECESARRY REPAIRS. MGR. TUFTS ARRANGED WITH THE SWITCH CREW TO REMOVE THE CAR BACK INTO THE INDUSTRY AND RELEASE THE CAR TO THE SHIPPER FOR REPAIRS.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY WILL THERMAN OPERTIONS, EAST YARD,LOS ANGLES, WHO REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR. DEVELOPED CAR DEPARTMENT FORCES HAD INSPECTED A CUT OF CARS IN BOWL TRACK #8, AND OBSERVED THE ABOVETANK CAR DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD,LOCATED THE CAR AND NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM BETWEEN THE BOTTOMTHE OUTLET CAP AND THE NOZZLE AT A RATE OF 2-3 DROPS PER MINUTE. A SMALL AREA IN BALLAST BELOW THEOUTLET (LESS THAN 1 SQUARE FOOT) WAS AFFECTED BY THE DRIPPING PRODUCT, INDICATING THE CAR HAD NOT BEEN MOVED FOR SOME TIME. THIS CAR IS EQUIPED WITH A TPO OPERATING HANDLE, WHICH WAS LOOSE. THE TOBOV HANDLE WAS TIRNED 1/2 A TURN, WHICH SECURED THE BOTTOM VALVE AND STOPPED THE LEAK. THE TOBOV PACKING GLAND WAS TIGHT, AND WAS NOT LOOSEND TO INSPECT THE PACKING MATERIAL. WHILE INSPECTING THE TOP LIQUID AND AIR LINE CONNECTIONS,NOTED THE AIR LINE PLUG WAS OFF. THE AIR LINE BALL VALVE WAS CLOSED, AND NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED. THE PLUG WAS PLACED BACK ON THE AIR LINE AND PROPERLY SECURED. ATTEMPTS TO TIGHTEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP PROVED FUTILE AS THERE WAS NO MOVEMENT AT ALL, INDICATING THE CAP GASKET MAY  BE DETERIORATED. THE AREA AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET AFFECTED BY THE PRODUCT WAS DECONED WITH A VINGER SOLUTION. THE AREA BETWEEN THE TRACKS WAS ALSO ADDRESSED WITH A VINEGAR SOLUTION UNTIL NEUTRAL PH LEVELS WERE OBTAINED. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE THE CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: ON 9/10/98 AT 21:49 MR. W.M. SEABAUGH REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED OF A STRONG ODOR REPORTEDLY COMMING FROM AN AREA WHERE SEVERAL TANK CAR WERE LOCATED IN THE UPRR YARD, PINE BLUFF, AR. MR.SEABAUGH IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE ARRIVING AT 22:45 HRS. AT 23:05 HRS, MR. SEABAUGH BEGAN INSPECTING TANK CARS LOCATED ON TRACK #51. SEABAUGH NOTED STRONG ODOR NEAR TANK CAR DCLX 3006. DURING INSPECTION OF PROTECTIVE HOUSING HE NOTED A HISSING SOUND. SEABAUGH REMOVED CABLE SEAL (NO NUMBER INDICATED ON SEAL) AND DISCOVERED THE FOLLOWING: * A END MIDLAND VALVE NOT FULLY CLOSED AND 1 INCH PLUG IN OUTLET PORT LOOSE. CORRECTIVE ACTION ENTAILED CLOSING VALVE BY APPLYING HALF TURN ON OPERATING WHEEL AND MAKING 1 INCH PLUG TOOL TIGHT(1 AND 1/2 TURNS). THIS ACTION STOPPED APPARENT VAPOR LEAK EMITTING FROM THIS VALVE. ADDITIONAL EFFORTS UINCLUDED TIGHTENING LEFT SIDE VAPOR VALVE AND 1 INCH PLUG LOCATED IN SAME . SEABAUGH NOTED DOW CHEMICAL CHLORINE CUSTOMER RESPONSE CARD LOCATED INSIDE PROTECTIVE HOUSING THAT INDICATED TANK CAR LOADED AND INSOECTED BY SMITH/ROSS. SEABAUGH CLOSED COVER AND APPLIED SEAL# UPRR EMG 004234. TANK CAR RELEASED AT 23:35 HRS. UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER UPDATED AND ADVISED TO MAKE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 7:15 PM AMERICAN EAGLE OPERATIONS IN ABILENE RECEIVED A AIRING RADIO CALL FOR AA3839 EN ROUTE FROM DALLAS/ FORT WORTH (DFW) TO MIDLAND-ODESSA (MAF).  THE CREW WAS ATTEMPTING TO CONTACT DISPATCH AND REPORTED STRONG FUMES IN THE AIRCRAFT CABIN THAT APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM A PASSENGER'S CARRY-ON BAGGAGE. THEY INITIALLY BELIEVED THE SOURCE TO BE A CAN OR CANISTER OF PAINT THAT WAS LEAKING OR PUNCTURED.  THE CREW INFORMED DISPATCH THEY WERE 20 MILES OUT OF ABILENE AND DIVERTING TO LAND. THE AIRCRAFT TOUCHED DOWN AT 1936 HRS AND ARRIVED AT THE GATE AT 1938 HRS. MAINTENANCE HAS BEEN ADVISED AND WERE ON HAND TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  THE CREW AND PASSENGERS DE PLANED ALMOST IMMEDIATELY. IT WAS NOTED BY BOTH MAINTENANCE AND AIRLINE PERSONNEL THAT THE FUMES COULD BE DETECTED FROM A CONSIDERABLE DISTANCE, OUTSIDE THE AIRCRAFT.  THE SUSPECT ITEM OF BAGGAGE WAS CONFISCATED FOR CLOSER EXAMINATION AND INVESTIGATION. THE PASSENGERS, LESS THE INDIVIDUAL OWNING THE SUSPECT CARRY-ON ITEM, WERE RE-CLAIMED BY ITS SECURITY AND BOARDED ANOTHER AIRCRAFT, WHICH DEPARTED ABILENE FOR MIDLAND ODESSA AT 2109.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 17, 1998 AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS, TW COMPANY WAS NOTIFIED BY MS. KARLA SIMMONS OF TRI STATE MOTOR TRANSIT OF A POSSIBLE LEAKING ONE CUBIC YARD BULK CONTAINER.   THE CONTAINER HAD HAZARDOUS WASTE CONTAINING LEAD, CHROMIUM, AND SILVER.  THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY FAILURE OF  THE CARDBOARD SEAM.  THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED IN THE VAN WITH A SMALL RELEASE UPON THE GROUND. MR. PARKINSON ARRIVED ON SITE AT 1720 HOURS, TO ASSESS THE SITUATION AS REQUESTED. MR PARKINSON MET WITH THE DRIVER RICHARD THOMAS.  THE DRIVER WENT OVER THE SITUATION AND PROCEEDED TO OPEN THE DOORS.  ONE OF THE ONE CUBIC YARD SUPER BOXES HAD THE CORNER SEAM BREAK WHICH ALLOWED THE PLASTIC BAG LINER TO ESCAPE.  THE LINER HAD A SMALL TEAR IN IT RELEASING PRODUCT.  THERE WAS NO WAY TO PATCH OR MOVE THE CONTAINER WITHOUT IT COMPLETELY FAILING.  IT WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERRED INTO OTHER CONTAINERS.  TW COMPANY'S RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED AND ARRIVED AT THE SITE, AT 1820 HOURS.  THEY IMMEDIATELY SET UP EQUIPMENT TO RE MEDIATE THE SITUATION.  MS KARLA SIMMONS WAS LEFT AN UPDATE OF THE SITUATION.  THE TRUCK WAS FOUND TO HAVE POISONS, FLAMMABLE SOLIDS, DANGEROUS WHEN WET, FLAMMABLES, AND CORROSIVES ON IT.

column168: At approximately 1810 hours, Illinois Central Trainmaster, Orrell advised the operation control center that tank car scmx 4328 (a load of petroleum distillates) was leaking from the bottom outlet valve in track c-17 at our Memphis yard. Area has been isolated and operations stopped. Illinois Central haz mat technician, Greg Henshaw, was sent to the scene and found that the bottom outlet handle was outside the locked keeper and had worked open a little during transportation. The keeper was in place and secured with shipper seal Shell DPCP 5459. Greg removed the shipper seal, placed the handle in the proper place and re-sealed with ICGRR UL13999 seal. He also tightened the bottom outlet cap. Car was returned to transportation and normal yard operations started again.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED.  THE CONTAINER WAS BEING SORTED WHEN IT WAS INADVERTENTLY TIPPED OVER.  THE CONTAINER STARTED TO RELEASE VAPOR FOLLOWED BY A LIQUID.  THE LIQUID WAS FREE STANDING LIQUID NITROGEN USED AS A COOLING MEDIUM FOR BIOLOGICAL SPECIMENS. THE SHIPPER WAS ATTEMPTING TO UTILIZE THE EXCEPTION WHICH ALLOWS THE TRANSPORTATION OF BIOLOGICAL SPECIMENS IN CRYOGENIC MATERIALS I.E. HELIUM, LIQUID NITROGEN ETC... THE EXCEPTION ALLOWS A SPECIALIZED CONTAINER CALLED A DRY DEWAR TO BE USED FOR THE CONTAINMENT OF THE SPECIMENS.  THE EXCEPTION STIPULATES THAT THE COOLING MEDIUM DOES NOT HAVE TO BE DECLARED AS DANGEROUS GOODS UNDER THE EXISTING DOMESTIC HMRS AND INTERNATIONAL REGULATIONS PROVIDED THAT THE ITEM IS CONTAINED IN SUCH A MANNER THAT NO FREE STANDING LIQUID IS PRESENT THAT COULD RELEASE FROM THE CONTAINER CAUSING PROPERTY DAMAGE OR PHYSICAL INJURY.  IF THE DESIGN OF THE CONTAINER DOES NOT ALLOW THAT TO HAPPEN OR THE CONTAINER IS NOT BLED PROPERLY AFTER FILLING THEN IT CONSTITUTES A VIOLATION  OF THE EXCEPTION.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKING OR LABELS OTHERWISE EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE CONTAINER NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR DISPOSITION.

H.L. BART WAS NOTIFIED BY MECHANICAL MANAGER WILKINS OF THE P.T.R.A. RAILROAD, OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT THE PTRA MANCHESTER YARD.  TANK CAR GATX40086 WAS LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE DUE TO AN OVERLOAD CONDITION.  APPROXIMATELY 2000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS REDUCED AND CAR FORWARDED TO BILLED DESTINATION.  SHIPPER ADVANCED AROMATIC AT BAYTOWN, TEXAS WAS NOTIFIED OF THE OVERLOADED CONDITION AND DISPATCHED TANK TRUCKS TO RECEIVE THE PRODUCT.

UPRR HOUSTON CORRIDOR MANAGER REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 47074 WAS LEAKING A BRIGHT BLUE FLUORESCENT LIQUID FROM THE BOTTOM FITTINGS. THE CAR WAS SET OUT TO HOLDER SIDING.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET CARTER AND CAR FORMAN CASEY DYER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THE CAR DRIPPING MOLTEN (ON FIRE) MATERIAL FROM THE JACKET AT THE BOTTOM VALVE AND HEATER COIL OUTLET PIPE.  DIRT WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK TO CONTROL ANY FIRE.  STEAM/SMOKE WAS ALSO RISING FROM THE JACKET AREA AROUND THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND VALVE SETUP.  ROB YARBOROUGH, PHILLIPS 66, 409-235-2661, WAS ADVISED VIA CHEMTREC. MR. YARBOROUGH STATED EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WOULD RESPOND TO DEAL WITH CAR.  THE MATERIAL LEAKING STOPPED BEING MOLTEN AROUND 0700 HROS., DATE.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE INSULATION HAD BEEN ON FIRE AND THAT THERE WAS A SMALL LEAK SOMEWHERE IN THE TANK.  THE MOLTEN MATERIAL DRIPPING OUT WAS A COMBINATION OF THESE.  FOUR OPENINGS (2 ON EACH SIDE) WERE CUT INTO THE CAR JACKET BY PHILLIPS 66 AND THE ABILENE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  WATER WAS FORCED INTO THESE OPENINGS AND AROUND THE MANWAY NOZZLE, PUTTING OUT ANY LINGERING FIRE OR SMOLDERING.  THE LEAK STOPPED AND PRODUCT SOLIDIFIED.  CAR WAS MONITORED FOR 12 HOURS AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  IT WAS SET TO NATIONAL RAILWAY, ROSCOE, TX. TO BE OFF LOADED AND REPAIRED.

uprr car foreman reported tank car utlx83608 was a strong ammonia odor.  Car was located just west of the centennial rip track awaiting other repairs.  Uprr cts manager Arla Roquet Carter responded to the scene and found the packing gland nut 2 1/2 turns loose.  The nut was tightened and the leak stopped.  Car was released for movement at 1100 hrs.  Mrs. Carter notified rmcc and requested they call chemtrec and the emg help desk.

column168: ILLINOIS CENTRAL TRAIN CREW REPORTED PRODUCT COMING FROM TOP OF CAR. UPON INSPECTION FOUND THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED. SHIPPER, RHODIA WAS CALLED AND JERRY PIERROTTIE WITH THE SHIPPER ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND REPLACED THE DISC.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR CONTINUED MOVEMENT.

JONES DRIVER, RICHARD FISHER, WAS RED LIGHTED AT CORDILLA TRUCK SCALES AND INSTRUCTED TO PULL OVER TO ISOLATION AREA. UPON CLOSE INSPECTION BY THE HIGHWAY PATROL THEY POINTED OUT THAT THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF CAUSTIC ON THE BED OF THE TRAILER. HE WAS THEN INSTRUCTED TO CONTACT JONES CHEMICALS, MILPITAS TO SEND UP A RESPONSE TEAM. WE, IN TURN, CONTACTED SIERRA CHEMICALS, SACRAMENTO TO BRING AN EMPTY TOTE CONTAINER TO CORDILLA ALONG WITH A PUMP SO THAT WE COULD TRANSFER THE MATERIAL. OUR RESPONSE PERSON MET WITH SIERRA CHEMICALS AT THE CORDILLA TRUCK SCALES AND TRANSFERRED ALL OF THE MATERIAL FROM OUR TOTE TO THE CUSTOMERS TOTE. DURING THIS PROCESS CHP HAD THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT TO STAND BY UNTIL ALL OF THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED SAFELY. AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE.

Opened trailer door and could smell an odor. Employee, Zachary Davis, informed the under sign (Joe Legrand), that the shipment was damaged. I told him to put the container on Conway's back dock which is open and away from personnel. There was no haz mat phone number listed on the coso/ bill of lading. Larry Rilaes, FOS, called information who supplied shipper telephone number and contacted Chip Mclendon, safety director for Conway, the same day. The shipment was placed in an empty trailer that was sealed and locked and was moved to an area in the yard that was safe and would not be disturbed and waited for further instructions. Additional note: To the best of my knowledge, when I first saw the spillage I thought that it was liquid. Upon further examination I found it to be granular in nature. It appeared to be a handful that was swept up and put with the container. Upon discussion with the driver from Fort Smith, Arkansas, he advised me that the shipment had been damaged at their facility when they loaded it on the trailer that was brought to the Shreveport terminal.
